The FCS program is looking for an assortment of sewing supplies. I am excited to see a growing number of students in my Creative Textiles class and could use some additional supplies. If anyone would be willing to donate any items that they no longer use/need we would greatly appreciate it!
We could use fabric (even scraps to practice), thread, sewing gauges, knitting and crocheting supplies (yarn and needles), and embroidery supplies. Please contact Mrs. Peters if you have any questions.

post_text:
By invitation only:
Meridian Graduation 2020
Saturday, June 27 2:00pm

There will still be some limitations. Currently, with the number restriction, we are asking each graduate family to invite a maximum total of 12 people.

The current DHM measures also ask that home celebrations still be smaller. The current number is 25 at a gathering. This number may increase through the month of June.

There will be some changes to the ceremony to help with the social distancing requirements.

We will STRIV the graduation ceremony as well for those who will not be able to attend.

We ask graduates to ask your attendees to follow the social distancing requirements. Please allow 6' from people not living in your home. Masks are not required but definitely appreciated.

Thank you all for your understanding as we work to provide a graduation experience for our seniors!

May 25 at 12:33 PM ¬∑

....FLASH FLOOD WATCH NOW IN EFFECT THROUGH 7PM THIS EVENING...

The Flash Flood Watch is now in effect for

* Portions of southwest Iowa and Nebraska, including the following areas, in southwest Iowa, Fremont, Mills, Montgomery, and Page. In Nebraska, Boone, Butler, Cass, Gage,
Jefferson, Johnson, Lancaster, Nemaha, Otoe, Pawnee, Platte, Richardson, Saline, and Seward.

* Through 7 PM this evening

* Showers and thunderstorms are expected to overspread the area tonight into Monday. The soil is already saturated in some areas, so much of the rainfall will run off and potentially
lead to flash flooding.

* Additional rainfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches will be possible in the watch area.

PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

A Flash Flood Watch means that conditions may develop that lead to flash flooding. Flash flooding is a very dangerous situation.

You should monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action should Flash Flood Warnings be issued.

* Flash Flood Watch for portions of southwest Iowa and Nebraska, including the following areas, in southwest Iowa, Fremont, Mills, Montgomery, and Page. In Nebraska, Butler, Cass, Gage, Jefferson, Johnson, Lancaster, Nemaha, Otoe, Pawnee, Platte, Richardson, Saline, and Seward.

* From 4pm this afternoon through noon Monday.

* Heavy rain has saturated soils over parts of eastern Nebraska the past few days. Soils are not quite as wet in southwest Iowa.

* Rainfall amounts from 1 to 3 inches will be possible in the watch area, and isolated amounts of over 3 inches could occur.

PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

You should monitor later forecasts and be prepared to take action should Flash Flood Warnings be issued.

Every year, many elementary students look forward to the elementary track meet. However, like many other events that take place in the 4th quarter, the elementary track meet was canceled due to COVID-19. Or so we thought.

This past week, elementary students were given the opportunity to participate in the elementary track meet, COVID-19 style. Students were given 3 challenges, with 3 events in each challenge. The "1 minute challenge" had students calculate how many exercises they could do in 1 minute. The "endurance challenge" had students see how long they could last when completing each exercise. Finally, if students had the equipment needed they were able to participate in the optional "bonus challenge".

All students that submitted their results gave an AMAZING effort. Below is the link for the track meet results. The top 3 students per class are listed for each event. Thank you to all that participated! We hope you had fun with this activity! Have a great summer!

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1g1wGEXyhZmqM6_1DuIALnjAU1opIHOENdgj-AnIvsQ4/edit?usp=sharing

From Public Health Solutions:

PLEASE SHARE THE FOLLOWING WITH YOUR NETWORK ‚Äì ESPECIALLY PARENTS:

Nebraska is piloting a searchable database of licensed child care providers at https://www.nechildcarereferral.org/

During the COVID-19 pandemic, many essential workers are desperate to find safe places for their children. This website can help those who need quality emergency child care find it. It is also a valuable tool for the hundreds of licensed child care professionals struggling to keep their businesses open.

Thank you for all you do and we are eager for the day when we can meet as a group again and continue the great coalition work being done for children and families in Jefferson county!

Elementary students will have items picked up on Monday‚Äôs packet route. Please have these items ready to be picked up next Monday, May 18. Please be sure someone is at home so we can pick up chrome books. If you will not be home, please call the school and make an appointment with Trish.

Also, if your student has an older sibling in JH/HS that is already coming in, you may send the chrome book with them.

Please let the school know if you will not be available Monday for pickup and which option you will use to get chrome books returned.

Thank you!

post_text:
Request for recruiting election poll workers for the upcoming Jefferson County Primary Election on May 12th.

If they are at least 18, there are no restrictions.

Qualifications for workers: Must be a registered voter in Jefferson County, able to read and write English, available for poll worker training (2 hours via zoom), have good eyesight and hearing, cannot be a candidate appearing on the Primary ballot and able to work from 7 a.m. to after 8 p.m. to close the polls

If you are interested please contact Kris Riggle as soon as possible 402-729-6818.

Here is some information from the 10/11 news report about the increase of mental health calls: If you or someone you know is struggling, there are resources available.

CenterPointe offers crisis services for adults and juveniles. They operate the Crisis Line, 402 475-6695. This number is answered 24 hours a day, seven days a week. The Crisis Text Line can be reached by texting HOME to 741741.

The Mental Health Association of Nebraska is a peer-run organization. Their Warm Line can be reached at 402-261-5959.

The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline offers 24/7 free and confidential support at 1-800-273-8255.

We have attached the current Directive Health Measure (DHM) issued by the Govenor last evening. This includes all of the rest of the counties that were not in the DHM before.

This is a very serious pandemic. It has infected young and old, healthy and ill. We need to follow this directive so the Govenor will not have to break down and issue a stay at home measure. This would not be good.

As of this post there is NO positives for Jefferson, Saline, Fillmore and Thayer Counties in Public Health Solutions health district. Gage has 2. This will change.

Stay home as much as you can. We are all host for this bug. Most of us will never get sick from COVID-19, but we can/will carry it to someone that will get sick or even worse pass away.

Remember you are contagious before you even have the symptoms. We are not virus free even when we feel good. This is why the doctors tell folks to stay home for 14 days. When you get the symptoms it‚Äôs too late you have already infected others.

Public Health Solutions District Health Department
March 23 at 1:16 PM ¬∑

So what exactly does "flattening the curve" mean?
‚Äì "The phrase ‚Äúflattening the curve" refers to the same potential number of cases appearing over a greater period of time. When a spike in cases occurs, health care resources can be overwhelmed. A flatter curve is slower, allowing people to recover and hospitals can continue to provide care to families, friends and neighbors who need it. Flattening the curve means everybody does their part to reduce spread for as long as possible."

See the latest news release from DHHS, http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Flattening-the-Curve-History-Tells-Us-Why-Community-Mitigation-Strategies-Matter.aspx

Visit the CDC to learn more about community mitigation strategies, https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/index.html

Jefferson & Saline County Emergency Management
October 29, 2019 at 11:07 AM ¬∑

Winter is here.

Be careful this morning on your commute to work and school. There could be slick spots on roads, parking lots, driveways and sidewalks.

From the NWS:

WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY WILL BE IN EFFECT FROM MIDNIGHT TONIGHT TO 1 AM CDT THURSDAY

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches. Highest totals along the Nebraska Kansas border.

* WHERE...Portions of east central and southeast Nebraska and southwest Iowa.

* WHEN...From midnight tonight to 1 AM CDT Thursday.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening commute.
